  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Life-Saving Emergency Health and Referral Services to Conflict-Affected People in Paktika and Nuristan Provinces</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">With this project proposal, International Medical Corps UK aims to strengthen the emergency health and trauma care including referral services in the most conflict-affected areas of Paktika and Nuristan Provinces. The proposed program will increase access to quality emergency trauma care services through establishing 2 standalone First Aid Trauma Posts (FATPs) in Barmal District of Paktika and Want-Waigal District of Nuristan Province (one FATP per target district) as well as continuation of the emergency health services provided by the previously established FATP at the Barikot area of Kamdish District, Nuristan. These FATPs will ensure patients&#x2019; stabilization/treatment and when necessary, the referral of the severe trauma cases to other high level trauma centers or Health Facilities (HFs). In order to provide timely and standard referral, International Medical Corps will make available three standard ambulances (one at each FATP) equipped and supplied with all necessary items to provide first aid and basic life support.

In addition, International Medical Corps will provide emergency medical supplies and medical equipment to the Emergency Room (ER) that will be fully constructed and ready to use by October 2016 in Duab District Hospital (DH) in Nuristan, as well as provide trainings on Basic Life Support (BLS) and Psychological First Aid (PFA) to the newly recruited health staff of the proposed FATPs, which will help these facilities to provide adequate and timely responses and care without unacceptable mortality and/or morbidity. Furthermore, International Medical Corps will organize a training for the ambulance drivers and paramedics on first aid and mobile trauma services.

The proposed intervention will primarily serve the conflict-affected population in Want-Waigal, Duab and Kamdish districts of Nuristan Province as well as Barmal District of Paktika Province. International Medical Corps has coordinated all the proposed activities with the Health Cluster and the BPHS implementer in Paktika (OHPM). International Medical Corps will be signing a MoU with OHPM at the beginning of the project. The Health Cluster was very supportive of the proposed activities including the continuation of services through the existing FATP in Kamdish</narrative>
  </description>
